data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for each case:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0);
    Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count);          // failure shows actual count

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);   // if applicable
    // For predicate-based checks, keep LINQ but wrap:
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive),
        "Expected all users to be active");       // add a message for clarity

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3);
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);              // failure shows "Expected:3 Actual:5"

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null);
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Why this matters** — `Assert.IsTrue` failures only say `"Expected: True, Actual: False"`. Specific assertions give diagnostic messages:

| Instead of | Use | Failure message |
|---|---|---|
| `IsTrue(x.Count == 3)` | `AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | "Expected:3 Actual:5" |
| `IsTrue(x != null)` | `IsNotNull(x)` | "Assert.IsNotNull failed" |
| `IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` | "Expected not:0 Actual:0" |
| `IsTrue(a.Contains(b))` | `CollectionAssert.Contains(a, b)` | shows missing element |

Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods: `AreEqual` (ordered), `AreEquivalent` (unordered), `AllItemsAreUnique`, `IsSubsetOf`, and `Contains`/`DoesNotContain`.
